Project Background: There are multiple pathways for students to access the computer science and informatics major at UMass. Both majors are âclosedâ majors which means that students must apply to the major either via the UMass admissions process or via an internal major change once already enrolled at UMass. Both methods are very competitive. Computer Science as a field struggles with diversity of representation as women and people from historically marginalized groups are significantly underrepresented in the field. One general hypothesis suggests that by making Computer Science more competitive, the discipline becomes less appealing to those who already have to overcome disadvantages due to their marginalized status in the field and within society. Another dimension of marginalization that has historically been difficult to measure is economic class. While not a perfect correlation, my studies over the past few years have shown that those from wealthier backgrounds are more likely to have attended a high school in the US offering Advanced Placement courses and access to the Advanced Placement test for Computer Science, known as AP CSA. The first part of my studies began with an observation that a large number of students enter the CS major via admissions with AP credit for computer science. In previous work, I engaged in hypothesis testing to determine if students entering the final programming course via AP credit performed the same or differently than those students who entered that class via the normal pre-requisite course here at UMass.

Within the CS and Informatics majors, there are introductory programming classes that all students must take. Students score either a 4 or 5 on the CS A AP exam may enter 187 (the final course in the programming sequence at the time of my prior study) as newly admitted students. These AP scores are considered evidence of equivalent skill mastery to that achieved from the posted pre-requisites for the course. As a result, the null hypothesis would have been that there should be no difference in performance when comparing the grade mean of one group (the AP group) with the the other group (the pre-requisite class group). In my analysis, I learned that within a 99% confidence interval and p-value of .005, students who entered 187 via the AP exam are likely to have a higher grade in 187 by at least a .5 difference. In sum, the means for both groups are different, and I reject the null hypothesis.

Having learned that there is some evidence to suggest that students entering with AP exam credit for computer science have a performance advantage, and seeing that one third to one half of all entering CS majors have AP CSA credit, I wondered if there is an admissions advantage to having this AP credit and if that advantage is corresponding to a particular identity feature, such as economic class.

Research Question: I want to know who has access to the AP CSA exam and if this access is prioritizing students with particular identity features. In this case, a null hypothesis might be that access to the CS AP is not determined based on race, gender, or economic class as the public school system in Massachusets is required to serve all students equally, and AP computer science is a class that has existed in the public school system for decades. In order to explore this research question, I need to be able to explore data on AP CSA access and performance that enables me to make correlations between that access and performance to identity features of the students taking these exams. The State of Massachusetts does publish data on all AP exam results, by school district, and broken down by race and gender. The State also publishes data on the school districts themselves, including their funding status/amounts, graduation rates, and size of their senior cohorts.

Data Exploration: To begin, I am importing a large dataset from the 2022-2023 AP exam test statistics for the state of Massachusetts, broken down by school district name. There are multiple data sets as the site permits some tailoring of the data according to various selection criteria. One challenge of this data is that AP Performance is not reported for enrollments of fewer than 10 per district. That data can be accessed at the following URL where one has to set the selection for year before generating an automatic download of a .csv file. (see this website to generate a download of the CSV file used: https://profiles.doe.mass.edu/statereport/ap.aspx).

I now have a dataset that contains the scores by school district for the AP CSA exam (the exam that results in credit for introductory programming) These data are also located in CSV files with one file per demographic criteria.

This dataset that I am starting with has one categorical column which lists the school district name, a numerical column listing the districtâs identifier code, the number of tests taken at the district as an integer, and the next five columns are the number of tests that earned a one, two, three, four or five. The last two columns are float/double columns that provide the percentage of tests taken at that district that earned either a failing score of a 1 or 2 or a passing score of 3,4,or 5. One way I will need to mutate the data is to create a new column that is percent of just 4 and 5 as UMass rarely accepts 3s as passing for any AP exam.This also has numeric variables such as expenditures per student, graduation rate, size of the senior cohort, and dropout rate.

Via an online search, I was able to learn that there are 306 total school districts in the state of Massachusetts, but not all offer the CS AP exam, and not all include high schools. One of the variables I want to examine has to do with school funding. One hypothesis is that higher funded schools are more likely to have AP exams available, and a further extrapolation of that assumption is that higher funded schools would be more likely to have their students earn 4s and 5s (scores most likely to result in receiving course completion credit at public universities) on their AP exams. I was able to find State of Massachusetts data on state expenditures per student per school district. I am going to use that information as a proxy for wealthy/well funded school district instead of using property values as I think there is a lesser chance of confounding variables being hidden in using state spending per student rather than using the likely source of the funding for that spending (property values). The downside to using this proxy is that it treats school districts as one entity and some districts may have more than one highschool, and each of those schools may have different spending per student values. I accessed this dataset at this URL where I selected the year before it automatically downloaded the resulting .CSV file: (https://profiles.doe.mass.edu/statereport/ppx.aspx)

I merged these data sets (CSA AP and State District expenditures and senior cohort information (see this site to make selections and generate a .csv file of each cohortâs graduation report:https://profiles.doe.mass.edu/statereport/gradrates.aspx ) using the unique school district code identifiers in MS excel because that was the fastest/most efficient process. The resulting dataset includes expenditure data, CSA AP data, and data on size of cohort and rate of graduation as mentioned above, but only for the districts that had CSA tests taken in the 2022-2023 school year. Scores of 1 or 2 on the CSA AP exam are almost always failing scores, and the values in those columns are counts - the number of tests taken with that score. Similarly, sometimes a 3 score and always a 4 or or a 5 score are considered âpassingâ scores and thus likely to result in AP credit at most colleges. The percent 1_2 and percent3_4_5 scores are percentages of tests taken at the district that earned one of those scores. As a reminder, detailed data on the score counts and rates for specific districtâs CSA AP tests taken are not included by the State when fewer than 10 exams were taken in that district and so those values are ânaâs in the dataset.

My data has 158 rows (school districts) and 22 columns. I still have a number of NAs in the score performance columns. This is due to the state not reporting detailed results when school districts have fewer than 10 AP exams completed. The above summary also shows me that the the median graduation rate in the state among those students who took the CSA exam is very high - 95%. This value is a long way from the 77.2 percent minimum in any one school district. Also of interest is the small number of tests taken. Despite the median senior cohort size being 242 students, the median number of CSA exams taken is only 11. This is very interesting to me. As computer science is the largest undergraduate major at UMass, it seems surprising that only about 5% proportionately of Massachusetts seniors are taking the AP exam for CS, suggesting a very small percentage of students are pursuing computer science in high school OR do not have access to the exam. One possible research question for the future might be to try to explore why this might be the case.

Total expenditures per pupil might be another interesting figure to explore since there is a 20K difference between the minimum and maximum value in the data set. Another research question might ask what relationship is there between the expenditures per student and the number of CSA exams taken? How do those values also correlate or not with the percentage of passing scores on the exam. #The following is attempting to reduce the measurement of cohort size by creating chunks of school district sizes based on sizes of the senior cohort for that district. The cut-offs for these are somewhat arbitrary.
Senior_chunks <- CSA_all %>%
  as_tibble() %>%
  mutate(
    Senior_cohort=case_when(
      Senior_cohort < 75 ~ "small",
      Senior_cohort > 75 & Senior_cohort < 250 ~ "medium",
      Senior_cohort>250 & Senior_cohort < 500 ~ "large",
      Senior_cohort >500 ~ "extra large"
      
    )
  )

Armed with this new information, that there is a disproportion in terms of number of tests taken per student in the senior cohorts, I decided to create a new column to explore this idea further. I am adding a column that calculates the ratio of tests taken vs students in the senior cohort. I am then going to visualize the distribution of data in that column, and then I am going to drill deeper into those rows with the highest ratios (closer to 1) and see what I can learn.

#the following code creates two new columns - the first is the ratio of exams taken per senior and the second is the percentage of exams taken that earned a score of a 4 or a 5
CSA_all2 <- CSA_all %>%
   mutate (Exams_per_senior = CSATestsTaken / Senior_cohort) %>%
   mutate (percent_4_5 = (four_score + five_score)/CSATestsTaken, na.rm = TRUE)

There are not a lot of conclusions to draw from these last two plots, but there are some interesting observations that I can make. The closer a school gets to having 1 AP exam per senior in schools where more than half of the test takers earn a high passing score of a 4 or a 5, the higher the graduation rate for that school. This correlation is weak so there is no linear relationship here - it isnât a perfect increase per unit x vs y. But, we can say that all students in this high passing category are also at schools with above a 90% graduation rate, except for 3. We can also say that there is a less likely correlation between the number of exams per senior and when a school district is more likely to have half or more test takers in this high scoring area. We see high scoring majorities even in districts where relatively few exams are taken with respect to the size of the senior cohort.

Conclusion To me, the data story in this project is one of access and opportunity. When CS AP exams are taken in a school district, a significant proportion, perhaps as many as half, are just as likely to earn high passing grades oa not, and through the other data explorations, there doesnât seem to be a strong correlation between any variable related to exam success. This is an important observation as a significant meta analysis of multiple datasets related to learning, learning speed, and achievement gaps has found that all students learn at about the same rate and that achievement gaps are the result of lack of access to opportunities for practice/learning experiences and not due to differences in learning rates (Koedinger et al 2023).

Another important observation is that of the 6 school districts with the highest number of CS A AP exams taken, 4 have significantly smaller senior cohorts when compared to the other 2, and, are overwhelmingly wealthy when looking at average home selling costs and median family income. The top exam district has a median single family home price of $975K and a median family income of over $200,000. It also is graded as less diverse overall and as having a very low (~5%) free and reduced lunch rate among students in that district (see https://www.niche.com/k12/d/lexington-public-schools-ma/ for more details). My conclusions from this project are that students do well on the CS A AP exam, regardless of expenditures per student, size of cohort, or number of exams taken. However, there is a disproportionate amount of access to the CS A AP in districts primarily populated by wealthy and very wealthy Massachusetts residents. This observation coupled with the research on the need to address lack of opportunity on closing achievement gaps emerges as driving a data story of CS AP access that is skewed toward students occupying the wealthiest communities in the state.
